flowRoot.flowPara: Endless loops in generators are allowed and often valid.
A generator function is defined like a regular function.
Every time yield is executed, the generator returns one value.
A non-infinite exhausted generator creates a StopIteration exception.

Generatoren are special Python functions that are executed only when a result is needed (lazy evaluation). They help e.g. writing efficient code for large data volumes and to represent infinite series. Python borrowed the concept from functional programming languages.
Calling a generator returns an interator from which values can be retrieved using next() or a for loop.
Many common Python functions are generators, e.g. range(), zip() und open().
Generators can be matrialized as a data structure with list() unless they are infinite.
